<paragraph id="8BB7368AD863FFEC3CB4FE8B31B1FAE7" blockId="54.[151,1058,305,385]" pageId="54" pageNumber="1013">
D i a g n o s i s: The stramineous color of the elytra, in combination with the incised black macula on the pronotal disc, will distinguish the members of this species from congeners. The genus 
<taxonomicName id="4C084D09D863FFEC3D59FED133C9FAE6" authorityName="Pic" authorityYear="1950" box="[378,502,363,384]" class="Insecta" family="Cleridae" genus="Pujoliclerus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="54" pageNumber="1019" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B97CEA98D863FFEC3D59FED133C9FAE6" box="[378,502,363,384]" italics="true" pageId="54" pageNumber="1013">Pujoliclerus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
PIC was revised in 2014 (
<bibRefCitation id="EF994B7BD863FFEC3EDFFED131BDFAE7" author="OPITZ W" box="[764,898,363,385]" pageId="54" pageNumber="1013" pagination="727 - 756" refId="ref53564" refString="OPITZ W. (2014 d): Classification, natural history, and evolution of the checkered beetle genus Pujoliclerus PIC (Coleoptera: Cleridae: Peloniinae). - The Coleopteristss Bulletin 68 (4): 727 - 756." type="journal article" year="2014">OPITZ 2014d</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BB7368AD863FFEC3CB4FE2A32C0F9DB" blockId="54.[151,1059,399,701]" pageId="54" pageNumber="1013">
D e s c r i p t i o n: Size: Length 5.0 mm; width 2.0 mm. Form: As in 
<figureCitation id="13332A0FD863FFEC3F5CFE3531EBFAC3" box="[895,980,399,421]" captionStart="Figs 338-341" captionStartId="112.[151,191,1510,1532]" captionTargetBox="[155,1060,195,1490]" captionTargetId="figure@112.[153,1061,195,1493]" captionTargetPageId="112" captionText="Figs 338-341: Habitus; (338) Pujoliclerus ariquemes; (339) P. catie; (340) P. cnecostus; (341) P. convexus." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3746830" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3746830/files/figure.png" pageId="54" pageNumber="1013">Fig. 340</figureCitation>
. Color: Cranium mostly testaceous, upper frons black; antenna black, except apex yellow; prothorax mostly testaceous, pronotal disc with incised black macula; mesothorax testaceous, infuscated; metathorax brown; elytra stramineous; prothoracic legs bicolored, femur mostly yellow, rest brown; mesothoracic and metathoracic legs yellow; abdomen brown. Head: Antenna (
<figureCitation id="13332A0FD863FFEC3DB1FDA133E2F954" box="[402,477,539,562]" captionStart="Figs 1-27" captionStartId="70.[151,191,1302,1324]" captionTargetBox="[155,1057,207,1268]" captionTargetId="figure@70.[155,1058,207,1283]" captionTargetPageId="70" captionText="Figs 1-27: Antennae; (1) Aphelocerus nodus; (2) A. copanus; (3) A. magnipannus; (4) A. yoro; (5) A. sparicapillus; (6) A. tigra. (7) A. nolus; (8) A. ligulus; (9) Perilypus schusteri; (10) P. apunctus; (11) P. virgulatus; (12) P. izabal; (13) P. alpinus; (14) Cregya fuscomacula; (15) Phonius versus; (16) Pujoliclerus ariquemes; (17) Pelonium falcatum; (18) Pujoliclerus cnecostus; (19) P. trunculus. (20) P. sentus; (21) P. testudinatus; (22) P. catie; (23) P. flavidus; (24) P. convexus; (25) P. meloinus; (26) P. mexicoensis; (27) P. tuxtlas." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3746746" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3746746/files/figure.png" pageId="54" pageNumber="1013">Fig. 18</figureCitation>
) capitate, 6 
<superScript id="7C7D9BC2D863FFEC3E7BFDA2305AF940" attach="left" box="[600,613,536,550]" fontSize="6" pageId="54" pageNumber="1013">th</superScript>
antennomere expanded, capitular antennomeres 8 and 9 triangular, antennomere 10 ovate; eyes large, coarsely facetted, eye as wide as frons (EW/FW 30/20). Thorax: Pronotum (
<figureCitation id="13332A0FD863FFEC3E98FDE93129F90C" box="[699,790,595,618]" captionStart="Figs 118-133" captionStartId="76.[151,191,1373,1395]" captionTargetBox="[152,1050,202,1340]" captionTargetId="figure@76.[152,1056,202,1357]" captionTargetPageId="76" captionText="Figs 118-133: Pronota; (118) Pujoliclerus abditus; (119) Nelsopelonium aspikelum; (120) Parapelonides naranjo; (121) Pujoliclerus lasiosus; (122) Neorthopleura rubra; (123) Pujoliclerus ariquemes; (124) Ichnea cerinis; (125) Ampleris amazon; (126) Pujoliclerus abditus; (127) P. dexsus; (128) Sirpa acara; (129) Madoniella aspera; (130) Pelonium tayrona; (131) Megatrachys irrasis; (132) Ordinis taxis; (133) Pujoliclerus cnecostus." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3746758" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3746758/files/figure.png" pageId="54" pageNumber="1013">Fig. 133</figureCitation>
) slightly oblong (PW/PL 75/83), disc finely punctate, lateral tubercles well developed; elytral asetiferous punctures striate, extend to elytral apical 4/5 
<superScript id="7C7D9BC2D863FFEC3E50FD3230BFF9F0" attach="left" box="[627,640,648,662]" fontSize="6" pageId="54" pageNumber="1013">th</superScript>
(EL/EW 220/60). Abdomen: Pygidium scutiform.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BB7368AD863FFEC3CB4FD773110F984" blockId="54.[151,815,717,739]" box="[151,815,717,739]" pageId="54" pageNumber="1013">
